{{Italic title}} [[File:Marshall Lind.jpg|thumb|180px|Marshall Lind (shown in 1973) was commissioner of the [[Alaska Department of Education]] from 1971 to 1982. He was the lawsuit's named defendant by virtue of his position.]] '''''Tobeluk vs. Lind''''' was a landmark case in Alaskan Native education. The 27 teenage plaintiffs brought suit against the State of Alaska, claiming that [[Native American boarding schools]] were discriminatory and unjust.<ref name=tobeluk>{{cite web|title=ANNA TOBELUK, et al., Plaintiffs, vs. MARSHALL LIND, et al., Defendants. No. 72-2450|url=http://www.alaskool.org/native_ed/law/tobeluk.html|accessdate=28 November 2014}}</ref> The case is widely known as the "Molly Hootch Case" after the first plaintiff named.<ref name=tobeluk/>
At the time of the case, Alaskan Native parents were forced to send their children away for schooling because of a lack of quality local educational facilities in their towns.<ref>http://voices.yahoo.com/equality-education-molly-hootch-case-ensured-5440371.html?cat=37</ref>{{unreliable source|date=September 2015}} Boarding schools had historically been used as a [[Cultural assimilation of Native Americans#Non-reservation boarding schools|tactic of assimilating]] Native students into white culture. Alaskan Native children were sent far from their parents for their secondary education, often heading to the contiguous 48 states and boarding with local non-Native families. They were thus immersed in a situation that was both geographically (Oregon, Oklahoma, etc.) and culturally removed from their place of origin. The plaintiffs alleged that this situation led to mistreatment of the Native students and a high dropout rate among them (65% within 2 years, in one documented case <ref>http://www.alaskool.org/native_ed/law/mhootch_erq.html</ref>), signs of educational inequality.<ref>http://right2education.wikispaces.com/Molly+Hootch</ref>
In October 1976, the signing of the Tobeluk [[Consent Decree]] <ref>http://www.alaskool.org/native_ed/law/tobeluk.html</ref><ref>https://www.nlm.nih.gov/nativevoices/timeline/544.html</ref> committed the government to building local high schools in Alaska, which they have since done with positive results on retention rates.{{Citation needed|date=April 2014}} The state by means of the consent decree agreed to create a secondary school in any village with at least fifteen high school-aged children.<ref name=Haycox>{{cite book|last1=Stephen|first1=Haycox|title=Alaska: An American Colony|date=2006|publisher=University of Washington Press|isbn=0295986298|page=285|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=natRq6WCu4oC&printsec=frontcover&dq=an+american+colony+Haycox&hl=en&sa=X&ei=TLN3VLKfNczIsASqqoLYDA&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=high%20school&f=false|accessdate=28 November 2014}}</ref>
